    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-11-15T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-11-15T06:00:00-05:00" n="128"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d128">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <gloss target="#t_JCS1">J. C. S.</gloss> Files</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Minutes of the Presidents Meeting With the Joint Chiefs of
                        Staff, November 15, 1943, 2 P.M., Presidents Cabin, U. S. S. “Iowa”</hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d128fn1">Present were <persName corresp="#p_RFD1"
                            >Roosevelt</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_LGA1">Leahy</persName>, <persName
                            corresp="#p_MGC1">Marshall</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_KWLM1"
                            >King</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_AHH1">Arnold</persName>,
                            <persName corresp="#p_BW1">Brown</persName>, and <persName
                            corresp="#p_RFB1">Royal</persName>. For additional excerpts from the
                        minutes of this meeting, see <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_194">p. 194</ref>.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <date ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-document-head" calendar="gregorian"
                        when="1943-11-15T14:00:00+03:00">November 15, 1943, 2 p.m.</date>
                </dateline>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">1. U. S. <hi rend="smallcaps">Delegation in Moscow To Proceed to
                            “<gloss target="#t_Sextant1">Sextant</gloss>”</hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">The President</hi> said that he desired a dispatch sent to
                    Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName> immediately upon
                    arrival in port telling him to come to the place for the <gloss
                        target="#t_Sextant1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sextant</hi>
                    </gloss> Conference, and bring with him General <persName corresp="#p_DJR1"
                        >Deane</persName>, Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BCE2">Bohlen</persName> of the
                    State Department, and General <persName corresp="#p_VHS1">Vandenburg</persName>
                        [<persName corresp="#p_VHS1">
                        <hi rend="italic">Vandenberg</hi>
                    </persName>].</p>
                <pb facs="0179" n="87" xml:id="pg_87"/>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">The Chiefs of Staff</hi> directed the Secretary<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d128fn2">Captain <persName corresp="#p_RFB1">Forrest B.
                            Royal</persName>.</note> to prepare an appropriate dispatch in
                    compliance with the President’s desires.<note n="3" xml:id="d128fn3">Message of
                        November 20, 1943, <hi rend="italic">post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_102">p.
                            102</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">The President</hi> then said that the big conference would
                    be held in Tehran. He then read a dispatch regarding the fact that Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> cannot come to <gloss
                        target="#t_Sextant1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sextant</hi>
                    </gloss> by 22 November.<note n="4" xml:id="d128fn4">See <persName
                            corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>’s first telegram of November 12,
                        1943, to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>, <hi rend="italic"
                            >ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_82">p. 82</ref>.</note> However, Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> will come to Tehran with
                    Marshal <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName> by the end of November.
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">The President</hi> added that it was vague as to why
                    Mr. <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> could not come by the 22nd,
                    but he inferred from the message that <persName corresp="#p_MVM1"
                        >Molotov</persName> was probably ill.<note n="5" xml:id="d128fn5">The last
                        two paragraphs of <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>’s second
                        telegram to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName> on November 12,
                        1943 (<hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_83">p. 83</ref>),
                        indicate that <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName> was disturbed
                        when he learned from <persName corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName> that
                            <persName corresp="#p_CKS1">Chiang</persName> would be in Cairo at the
                        same time as <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>. It appears,
                        however, that this telegram was not forwarded to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1"
                            >Roosevelt</persName> aboard the <hi rend="italic">Iowa;</hi> see
                        footnote 1 to <persName corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName>’s second
                        telegram to <persName corresp="#p_RFD1">Roosevelt</persName>, <hi
                            rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_82">p. 82</ref>. See also the
                        remarks on this subject by <persName corresp="#p_HWA2">Harriman</persName>
                        and <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName>, <hi rend="italic"
                            >post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_94">p. 94</ref>. <persName corresp="#p_CC2"
                            >Churchill</persName>’s telegram of November 10, 1943, to <persName
                            corresp="#p_SIV1">Stalin</persName> (<hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref
                            target="#pg_78">p. 78</ref>) had not indicated, however, that <persName
                            corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_CKS1"
                            >Chiang</persName> were to be included in the same discussions at Cairo.
                        Cf. Lohbeck, p. 203.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                <p rend="center">5. <hi rend="smallcaps">Telegram From Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="#p_WJG1">Winant</persName>
                    </hi>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">The President</hi> referred to a recent telegram received
                    from Ambassador <persName corresp="#p_WJG1">Winant</persName> in which it was
                    said that the Prime Minister was emphatically against the proposal that any U.
                    S. S. R. officer should be present at the <gloss target="#t_Sextant1">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Sextant</hi>
                    </gloss> Conference.<note n="6" xml:id="d128fn6">Telegram of November 4, 1943,
                            <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_64">p. 64</ref>.</note> It
                    was felt by Mr. <persName corresp="#p_CC2">Churchill</persName> that the
                    difficulty of military planning must be settled between the U. S. and British
                    Governments before any contact on this subject is made with the Soviet
                    Government. …</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
            </div>
